steps.description:
Spread a moist paper towel in between the cutting board and the counter to prevent the cutting board from sliding around. Soak the paper towel in water and squeeze out the excess moisture. This gives the towel just enough tension to prevent it and the cutting board from sliding around. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/18/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/18/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Do not let the towel stay soaked, though, since a soaked paper towel will be too slippery. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Note that this may not be necessary if you are using a no-slip silicone cutting mat. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f8/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f8/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make sure that your hands, the knife, and the cutting board are all clean before you begin. Use warm water and soap to clean your hands and all the supplies used for cutting the cabbage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Rinse the knife and cutting board with clean, running water to remove all soapy residue. Wipe dry with clean, dry paper towels. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/61/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/61/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Do not clean the cabbage yet. The cabbage should be rinsed after you cut it, not beforehand. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use your hands to peel off any tough or damaged outer leaves from the head of cabbage. Round heads of cabbage with tightly packed leaves have thick outer leaves. Even if these leaves are in good shape, you should still remove them before cutting the cabbage, since they tend to be tough and not especially appetizing. This is especially true if you plan on eating the cabbage raw. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Any wilted or discolored portions must also be removed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Flip the quarters over to reveal the cut sides. Cut a wedge at the bottom into the core of each quarter. Only cut away part of the core, however, not all of it. Keeping part of the core connected to the leaves will make it easier to keep the layers of leaves in each core held together. If you cut out the core completely, the leaves are likely to separate. The cabbage will still be edible, but the wedges will be ruined. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3d/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3d/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

While looking at the core, cut a triangular wedge into the top portion of the core but not all the way through it. Slice a large portion of the wedge away while leaving a thin layer behind. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9c/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9c/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you are anxious about cutting away some without cutting away too much, you could also simply leave the core intact. The core is tougher than the leaves, but it becomes tender and edible once cooked. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9c/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9c/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-9Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Gently rinse each wedge of cabbage under cool running water. Drain dry on clean paper towels. The inside of a cabbage is usually clean, but you should still rinse it under running water just to be on the safe side. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Hold the cabbage wedges over a colander in case any of the leaves separate and fall off under the pressure of the running water. The colander will catch the leaves while letting the water pass through. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d9/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d9/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You do not need to scrub the leaves when cleaning them. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e0/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e0/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

To dry the wedges after rinsing them, lay them out flat in a single layer on several layers of dry paper towels for a few minutes. The excess water should fall off on its own. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/94/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/94/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-11Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Gently rinse each wedge under cool, running water. Drain dry on layers of clean paper towels. Even though the inside of a cabbage is usually clean, you should still rinse it under running water just to be safe. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3b/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3b/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Hold the cabbage wedges over a colander in case any of the leaves break off under the pressure of the running water. The colander will catch the leaves while letting the running water pass through. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b2/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b2/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You should not scrub the leaves when cleaning them. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/18/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/18/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

To dry the wedges after rinsing them, lay them out in a single layer on a few dry paper towels for several minutes. The excess water should drain off on its own. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/27/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/27/Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Cut-a-Cabbage-Into-Wedges-Step-17Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
